<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How much grout do I need for a 100 sq ft tile job?", answer: "For 12×12 inch tile with 1/8 inch joints at 1/4 inch depth, 100 sq ft needs about 23 pounds of grout — one 25 pound bag covers the job comfortably. With wider 1/4 inch joints and the same tile, coverage drops to about 53 sq ft per 25 lb bag, so 100 sq ft needs 2 bags. Smaller tiles and larger joints dramatically increase grout use because they add more joint length per square foot." },
  { question: "How much grout per 25 lb bag?", answer: "For common combinations: 12×12 inch tile with 1/8 inch joints covers ~130 sq ft per 25 lb bag; 12×12 with 1/4 inch joints ~65 sq ft; 6×6 with 1/8 inch joints ~65 sq ft; subway tile (3×6) with 1/16 inch joints ~85 sq ft. Coverage varies by brand, so always check the bag label." },
  { question: "Sanded vs unsanded grout — same coverage?", answer: "Coverage is nearly identical because both are cement-based and have similar density. The difference is application: unsanded is for joints under 1/8 inch (glass, polished stone, narrow-set subway), sanded is for joints 1/8 inch and wider. Using unsanded on wide joints leaves cracks; using sanded on glass can scratch it. Coverage calculations in pounds are the same either way." },
  { question: "Do I need extra grout for waste?", answer: "Yes — add 10 percent for cutting, mixing waste, and touch-ups. The calculator includes a configurable waste percentage, defaulted to 10. If the job has many cuts at edges, narrow borders, or complex patterns, bump it to 15 percent." },
  { question: "Is epoxy grout calculated the same way?", answer: "No. Epoxy grout is denser and comes in much smaller units — typically a 9 lb kit covers 40 to 60 sq ft of 12×12 tile with 1/8 inch joints. Always use the manufacturer's coverage chart for epoxy, not a cementitious grout calculator. This tool is calibrated for standard cement and polymer-modified cement grout." }
]) %>

